<h2>
    The AJAX Process
</h2>

<p>
    The <b>XMLHttpRequest</b> Object is supported on most modern browsers. It is 
    the <b>core of AJAX</b>. 
</p>

<h3>
    Create new Object
</h3>
<p>
    First, create a new XMLHttpRequest object:
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-js">// create new xhttp variable 
xhttp = new XMLHttpRequest();</code></pre>

<h3>
    Create callback function
</h3>
<p>
    The object then needs a callback function to tell JavaScript 
    what to do when the response is ready. A callback is a function 
    passed into another function as an argument. 
</p>

<pre><code class="lang-js">xhttp.onload = function() {
  // Code to run when response is ready
}
</code></pre>

<h3>
    Send Request
</h3>
<p>
    Finally, a request is sent with <code>open()</code> and <code>send()</code>:
</p>

<pre><code class="lang-js">xhttp.open("GET", "ajax_data.json");
xhttp.send();</code></pre>

<p>
    Now, smash all the code together:
</p>

<pre><code class="lang-js">// create new xhttp variable 
xhttp = new XMLHttpRequest();

xhttp.onload = function() {
  // Code to run when response is ready
}
xhttp.open("GET", "ajax_data.json");
xhttp.send();

</code></pre>

